Thank you very much for this awesome tutorial. I learned a lot from you.
But i found a bug in you Hamburger Menu. When you click a link, the menu doesn't close.
You need to write a little bit more of js and then it works.
I give a new class to the links from the hamburger menu ".header__mobilelink" and i add this to the js file:

const links = document.querySelectorAll('.header__mobilelink');


for (const link of links) { // Close Hamburger Menu after Link Click
    link.addEventListener('click', function(){
        console.log('click link');
        body.classList.remove('noscroll');
        header.classList.remove('open');
        fadeElems.forEach(function(element){
            element.classList.remove('fade-in');
            element.classList.add('fade-out');
        })
    })
};

Great video Jessica! I found a more concise solution to the problem you had with the fade-out animation on the Hamburger menu. You can add the fade-out animation to your base .overlay class to get the desired results. 

.overlay {
    opacity: 0;
    position: fixed;
    top: 3.75rem;
    right: 0px;
    bottom: 0px;
    left: 0px;
    background: linear-gradient($darkBlue, transparent);
    animation: fade-out 300ms ease-in-out forwards;
    z-index: -1; // Added to make text clickable (added for both .overlay and &.open.overlay)
}

That was an awesome work-around though, your critical thinking is next to none!
